messages.content: *"GLaM is a mixture of experts (MoE) model, a type of model that can be thought of as having different submodels (or experts) that are each specialized for different inputs. The experts in each layer are controlled by a gating network that activates experts based on the input data. For each token (generally a word or part of a word), the gating network selects the two most appropriate experts to process the data."*

--

Some of the newest large-scale language modeling methods depend on MoE to achieve SoTA with high parameter and compute efficiency. This is one of the central ideas of Bittensor, where servers deploy models trained to become experts on specific data, e.g. a language like French or Japanese, or different domains like code or scientific literature.

Queries to the Bittensor network are then routed to relevant experts, and the cool thing is that this routing process itself is also learned. This allows the network as a whole to achieve high parameter efficiency through incentivized deduplication of intelligence, where servers figure out which skills are missing and add those for improved reward.

Distillation underpins the Bittensor protocol. Invented by one of the machine learning founding fathers Geoffery Hinton, distillation is the technique of extracting knowledge from one machine learning system into another. This provides an avenue for creating small models with the performance of their teachers. We can use the larger computational power of a teacher to find a performant representational solution and then distill that knowledge into a smaller one.

Distillation is both a method of compression and a method of generalization. By learning in conjunction with the teacher, the student can even improve upon the teacher - overcoming the limitations of the teacher.

A very simple way to improve the performance of almost any machine learning
algorithm is to train many different models on the same data and then to

messages.content: At first glance the idea of distillation appears impossible. This is because ¨we tend to identify the knowledge in a trained model with the learned parameter values and this makes it hard to see how we can change the form of the model but keep the same knowledge.¨ (Hinton 2015)

However, A more abstract view of the knowledge, that frees it from any particular instantiation, is that it is a learned mapping from inputs to outputs. 

The function learned by the teacher model, as a side-effect of training, has additional information not available to a learner training for scratch, specifically, the teacher has attached probabilities to incorrect answers as well. We can learn also from how our mentor faired before us.

This is information is a guide for the student model which can help it solve the task at hand and also improve its own generalization.

An extensive report on the training of large-scale language models with the Bittensor template miner, utilizing masking, cyclic learning schedules, distillation, and mixture-of-experts. 1. Template miner can learn language modeling correctly.
2. Remote embeddings can transfer to local tasks.
3. Distillation outperforms normal training.

Machine learning/AI has gone through multiple phases in this same direction. Early AI systems were explicit, you wrote the solution by encoding your own knowledge into the system. Then SVMs and more statistical solutions. You defined the distribution and the kernel. Then very hands off, like neural networks, you define an abstract function and let the computer find the distribution. Then actual meta machine learning where you define the class of machine learning models and evolve them against a problem. And then beyond, where you evolve the meta machine learning against monetary constraints in a market.
Each level is stepping back farther and letting the system adapt under constraints.
The final level would be energetic constraints. But since AI is subservient to us, and we measure energy with money. Markets make sense as a proxy.

With data parallelism we replicate the model and have the data split and applied in parallel.

With model parallelism we replicate the data and have models split and updated in parallel.

The difference is that the data can be static, unlike the model which we dynamically update. Because of this the replication of the model in data parallelism requires continuous overhead to ensure consistent state. I.e. the all reduce step in federated learning. 

The over arching protocol will be the one that scales, in this case model parallelism. Nested below that will be layers of data parallelism. 

For instance Bittensor endpoints which replicate their models across multiple servers to service requests or train faster.


Model parallelism > data parallelism

Super corps like amazon already use similar tech to bittensor. They're called switch networks. But the difference is they are limited  by how much money they can spend on these things. Together, with all our compute combined, we can dwarf anything they create. The bitcoin network is actually 8 times more powerful than 500 of the worlds most powerful supercomputers.. Combined.

For your second question. Say google tomorrow hops in and introduces a bajillion computers.. They'll take total control of the network, and end up effectively producing tao and rewarding themselves. If there's no competition, then there's no  real value anymore.
However. If we grow large enough, then the most these corps can do is make a big splash, but they won't be able to monopolize it.
More practically speaking, right now they have their own internal switch nets, its too expensive for them to move to bittensor

If big tech already use switch networks to implement a bittensor-like network on a much smaller scale, what exactly is this statement from the blog referring to? Can't they share knowledge between models using their own network?

> Additionally, any value found by a combination of models working on the same modality (for example: text data, image data, etc.) is also lost. This is because models are inherently siloed to their environments. They are unable to share their knowledge with each other and so if any one model learns something that may be valuable to other models, it cannot share it with them to speed up their training.

Not exactly. I was saying big tech has similar tech, not *our* tech 🙂 

ML models benefit greatly from size. The more complicated and more layers it has, the more powerful it becomes. Big tech use switch networks to solve *one* problem, on *one* dataset, and effectively create *one* super massive model in the end. They're not sharing knowledge between models like we are. Instead they're building a model that is deployed over multiple computers, with its information being explicitly passed between them.

Bittensor is using *many* models, each with its own problem to solve. They learn from each other because they're not on many computers, each model is on one computer and is talking to other models. See what i mean by "similar"? 🙂

Once bittensor reaches critical mass, bittensors many models, interconnected together on the internet, will dwarf any massive switch network used by big tech, with the difference being that Bittensor consists of many smaller models talking to each other, as opposed to big techs one massive model spread across multiple computers
So, it's basically big tech's federated learning vs a whole new ML paradigm? 😲

Oh i love that you just said "federated learning"! You're on the right track.

Yes. bittensor miners are effectively using mixture of experts to select an *n* number of models to learn from on the bittensor network, then use distillation to learn from those models.
